{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487285","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487285"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:04:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:04:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"309"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"309","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/309"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.03,0.18,0.34,0.45]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"309"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101714"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"309","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/309"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2019-10-04T21:18:24+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-07T11:03:47+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2025-05-04T08:43:59+09:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-08-28 20:50:00"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"309"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9435"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84170"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"375"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1157"},{"type":"tags","id":"1493"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9600"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9998"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33808"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35252"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35305"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42052"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44859"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84170"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101714","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101714"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-year-old man is brought into the Emergency Department of a small rural hospital on Saturday after being hit on the left temple by a cricket ball earlier that afternoon. He fell to the ground and was not rousable for about ten seconds, but then got up and walked off to go and sit down. He soon began to develop a headache, prompting his presentation. He initially answered questions coherently, but now appears drowsy and complains of a widespread headache.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis Glasgow Coma Scale is recorded as 10. His pulse is 66/min, blood pressure 110/65 mmHg. His pupils are equal in size and reactive. The nearest regional neurosurgical centre is one hour\u0027s travel by road and an ambulance is available. The radiographer needs to be called in to the department as it is a weekend. They live 20 minutes drive from the hospital.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Regular observations in ED with a plan for discharge home later that day","Admit to the ward for further management","Intravenous mannitol","CT scan","Transfer to the regional neurosurgical centre"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question focusses on the initial assessment and likelihood of serious intracranial complications following a closed injury; with the added dynamic of being in a rural setting. This case is most likely an extradural haematoma, given the clear history of trauma, followed by a lucid period and then clinical deterioration over the next few hours. Key treatment for this is clot evacuation, which will ideally be done in a neurosurgical centre. Transfer should occur immediately if the Glasgow Coma Scale score is 3 - 8 or 9 - 13 and clinically deteriorating and the transfer will take less than two hours. If the patient was in a tertiary centre an early CT scan would be a priority in terms of confirming the diagnosis and planning management - but in this case, such an approach would only delay transfer of the patient. Intravenous mannitol can help reduce intracranial pressure, but in this case is less critical than \u003Cstrong\u003Eimmediate transfer to the regional neurosurgical centre\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegular observations in ED with a plan for discharge home later that day\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate given the patient\u0027s deteriorating condition and low Glasgow Coma Scale score, which indicates a potentially serious intracranial injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdmit to the ward for further management\u003C/strong\u003E would delay definitive treatment, which is urgent neurosurgical intervention. The patient\u0027s condition requires more than just observation or ward-based care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous mannitol\u003C/strong\u003E can be used to reduce intracranial pressure, but it is not a substitute for surgical intervention in the case of an epidural haematoma. The priority is to transfer the patient for potential surgical evacuation of the haematoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan\u003C/strong\u003E is important for diagnosis, but in this rural setting, waiting for a CT scan would delay the necessary transfer to a neurosurgical centre. The clinical presentation strongly suggests an epidural haematoma, and immediate transfer is the priority.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Transfer to a regional centre should be considered for all head injuries with a Glasgow Coma Scale score less than 10.","Epidural haematomas often present with a lucid interval followed by rapid deterioration, requiring urgent neurosurgical intervention."],"references":["Reed D.,\u00a0Initial Management of Closed Head Injury in Adults 2nd\u00a0Edition,\u00a0NSW Health [Internet]. Accessed on 6 Jan 2025. Available from: https://aci.health.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0003/195150/NSW-Health-Initial-management-closed-head-injuries-full.pdf","Vella MA, Crandall ML, Patel MB. Acute Management of Traumatic Brain Injury. Surg Clin North Am. 2017 Oct;97(5):1015-1030. doi: 10.1016/j.suc.2017.06.003. PMID: 28958355; PMCID: PMC5747306.","Nathanson MH, Andrzejowski J, Dinsmore J, Eynon CA, Ferguson K, Hooper T, Kashyap A, Kendall J, McCormack V, Shinde S, Smith A, Thomas E. Guidelines for safe transfer of the brain-injured patient: trauma and stroke, 2019: Guidelines from the Association of Anaesthetists and the Neuro Anaesthesia and Critical Care Society. Anaesthesia. 2020 Feb;75(2):234-246. doi: 10.1111/anae.14866. Epub 2019 Dec 1. PMID: 31788789."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84170"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"309"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84170","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84170"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-04T08:43:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-04T08:44:17+09:30","number":7,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2025-05-04T08:43:53+09:30","plagiarismScore":0,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-309-7.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250928%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250928T